description.text:
This is a replacement carriage for the CL-260 3d printer. It uses 12mm OD bearings from McMaster rather than the stock 11mm OD bearings that came with the original part (which I couldn't find easily). The bearings are kind of short, so I used 2 per axis (4 total).

These are the bearings I used:
https://www.mcmaster.com/#6658k68/=15xyrzg

I the first version of this carriage I had problems with my print splitting where the setscrews went into to hold the bearings as well as the hole for the screw that secures the hotend stripping out. So for this version I made those holes over sized and placed M3 threaded inserts into them.

The threaded inserts I used were these:
http://www.banggood.com/100pcs-M34mm-H62-Brass-Knurl-Nuts-DIY-Accessories-p-971077.html?p=13251118846620130525

You can probably google the best technique for installing these inserts but the way I do it is:

  1. Place the insert onto the tip of a soldering iron
  2. Push the insert into the hole in the 3d printed part as straight as possible until the insert is fully inserted.
  3. Quickly thread a screw all way through the insert and then back it out again. The idea is to clear the threads of any plastic that may have got on them while it is still warm and soft.

There are a couple of extra holes on the side of the carriage that I intended to use to attach a bracket to hold either an inductive bed sensor or a dial indicator for bed leveling, but I haven't tried either of those things yet.

title: 8mm Inductive Probe holder for Taz 5 w/ E3D Titan mount

description.text:
This is intended to be used with a side mount E3D titan extruder on the Lulzbot taz 5; it may work on the taz 6 as well, I'm not sure.

The best upgrade I ever did was to change to using an aluminum bed instead of a glass bed; this is the second best upgrade, though, which is just to add the inductive probe.

As you can see in the mockup picture this actually bolts to the extruder mount, not to the extruder plate itself, which should make it possible to swap extruders as long as the extruder you use is one which does not use the full width, such as the e3d extruder here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1965603

I actually used a different mount, but it's compatible with this one and I can't find the owner of the one I used so I'm not going to post it without permission.

The probe I used is the LJ18A3-8-Z/BX 8mm Approach Sensor NPN NO: http://a.co/8DG012q

(note with these instructions: you can use +12V instead of +24V in any place I say +24V)

Something to note about this probe, and please test this yourself to verify. When connected correctly you will provide it with +24V (Brown wire) and Ground (Black wire) and then the output (blue wire) will be 3.3v when it doesn't detect anything and 0v when it does. (NOTE: I know that reading the specs this looks like it's connected wrong -- it's not. If you use the wiring that you would naively expect you will blow up your board. There is no danger as long as you hook it up right -- but I take no responsibility regardless. Always check with a voltmeter before doing something like this.

On the stock taz if you run a +24V line to the probe you can then take the blue wire on your Z endstop to the blue wire on the probe and the black wire on the endstop to the black wire on the probe (ground is shared between the Z endstop and the 24VDC system) and it should work as a drop-in replacement for your Z sensor, at least from a wiring standpoint. You do not need any voltage divider with this probe.

You will need to enable auto bed leveling in your marlin firmware, however. That's a tough topic, but I'll answer what questions I can in the comments.

Edit Apr 10, 2016: I found that the previous version of the probe holder broke off a bit too easily, so I've made a new one following the same principles as the Prusa MK2S uses. This one doesn't require the hex nuts and is actually easier to install. If you print the "small" version you'll need to use a screwdriver to pull the circle open to insert or move the probe, but it shouldn't require any hardware to hold it; if you use the "normal" version then you should use a pair of M3 screws and a pair of M3 square nuts to tighten it after positioning it where you need it. This is both more durable and also easier to adjust.

V2 also holds the probe closer to the nozzle, which should give you slightly more accurate readings

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Make sure you put supports under the hex opening to hold the bolt; it'll be real difficult to tighten without that.

It is recommended to use tweezers or something similar to push the magnets fully into position.

All the magnets used are 8mm diameter X 3mm height neodymium magnets. (example: http://www.magnets365.com/50pcs-x-strong-disc-fridge-rare-earth-8mm-x-3mm-neodymium-magnets-n35.html)

The example shown has a wet sanded lid, giving it the dull look.

en plus de la palette il vous faut:

-du coton de demaquillage ou du papier essuie-tout

  • placez le fond blanc dans la palette (collez-le si possible).
  • decoupez le papier essuie-tout ou le coton a la forme de la palette, placez le dans la palette, mouillez le mais ne le saturez pas d'eau non plus.
  • il ne reste plus qu'a mettre le papier sulfurisé par dessus le coton, vous pouvez le faire bouillir pour le rendre un peu moins hydrofuge.

l'eau va légèrement humidifier le papier sulfurisé par capillarité, ainsi la peinture mettra plusieurs heures a sécher au lieu des quelques minutes d'une palette conventionnelle.

en cas de pause prolongée, le couvercle permettra de préserver encore plus longtemps la peinture.

lorsque la palette est trop utilisé, il suffit juste de changer le papier sulfurisé, le coton peu rester en place quelques temps, mais changez le de temps en temps pour éviter que de la moisissure se développe.

I had some difficulties printing the body due to some of the small supports needed. My problem was that the supports would not stick to the plate as well as the they should in this design and adding a raft was not possible because of my bed plate size . I added a small layer in the open areas at the same level as the first layer that would serve as a base for my supports and it worked better for me. this layer is only 0.4 mm thick (what my printer considered layer 1) and can easily be taken off similar to a support, but may need some sanding on the edges . There has been no overall design change to the body but it now has less chance of the print dislodging from the plate. If you are having difficulties printing this large part similar to what I did hopefully this will help.

I have also added the first layer of the original part so that if necessary you know where to remove the pieces that are from my design. simply print this layer and use it as a guide to remove the supports I have made.

title: Optimal Extensions for Transmitter - E010, Makerfire, H36...

description.text:
Hey!

This are optimal length extenders for very common drone transmitter (E010, H36, MakerFire and other similar drones). I've tried all kind of lengths but this one seems to be the best. This part goes between the transmitter and original transmitter knobs.

  • Tolerances are just right, they are not too hard or too loose to put on the transmitter!
  • Added fillet for easier attaching and fillet to make larger contact area to print.

NOTE: Make sure you orient file so that widest part is in the bottom - for good bed adhesion.

I've printed with 0.2mm layers, PLA, 40mm/s speed. :)

EDIT: 5 different pilots have this extensions and confirmed that this is actually the best size.

Happy flying!

Jure Korber

This is a double biquad wifi antenna. Since I am not that good with soldering copper piping and plate, I designed this 3d printed version!
I am not sure about the impedance matching of this antenna, I am not an expert, however, it works pretty well, I made a quick test tonight and was able to see about 20 wifi Access points just by pointing the dish in one general direction without taking care of adjusting it correctly..
Transmitting and Receiving works pretty well also, tested with aireplay-ng orienting the antenna correctly would give me 100% transmit packets on seemingly far APs..
Since I've just made the antenna, I didn't have much time to test it, but I'm convinced it's very effective!

You can follow the instructions of this site for detailled build of a double biquad, it will help understand the wiring and the assembly procedure: http://martybugs.net/wireless/biquad/double.cgi Materials:
  • Conductive adhesive tape
  • Non conductive adhesive tape
  • 2 M3 Bolts
  • 2 M3 Nuts
  • 1 RP-TNC Cable (I connect my antenna to a WRT54G-TM)
  • 1 Old Dish antenna with dual LNBF
    • Instructions:
  • Print all the parts once, except for the PlateType1 and PlateType2 which will be printed 2 times each.
  • Assemble the 4 plates, put your conductive tape on the upper surface.
  • Strip RP-TNC Cable so that it can slide in the Tube, but make sure to not put ground wire in the hole, only the white part with the center wire.
  • Put stripped cable end in center hole of 4 plates assembly
  • Connect / Tape the ground wire of the cable to the assembled plate
  • Put conductive tape around the tube
  • Put Tube on center hole with stripped cable end inside
  • Orient the Tube so that you can lay the 2 BiQuads horizontally.
  • Tape the Tube on the 4 plate assembly, make sure you have 0 resistance on the side of the tube and the plate assembly
  • Put Holder Plate on top of tube and screw the Holder Plate in place
  • Put the 2 BiQuads in the square holes of the Holder Plate, the 2 biquads ends should insert cleanly inside the tube
  • Apply conductive tape on all the surface of the 2 biquads, making sure to bridge the middle section of the 2 biquads. (Refer to the the website if this is not clear)
  • Connect ground conductive tape around the tube to the 2 biquads.
  • Connect the signal conductor in the middle of the tube to the 2 biquad ends, make sure ground and signal wire do not touch directly.
  • Apply silicon to exposed ends of the wire on the tube.
  • Secure the cable
  • Press Fit the assembly in the LNBF of a Dish (I unscrewed the top portion with the plastics of my LNBF, and simply pressed the biquad assembly in place, it's secured enough for my use)

Boitier permettant d’intégrer un switch end-stop. Pour Dagoma DiscoEasy 200 avec l'option écran.

Principe :
Le switch detecte qu'il n'y à plus de filament.
L'imprimante se met en pause et émet des bits jusqu'au changement de filament
La tete se positionne à l'extrémité du plateau
L'ecran affiche l'attente du changement de filament
Une fois le filament changé, il suffit de valider avec le bouton de l'écran pour poursuivre l'impression là où elle c'est arrêtée.

Matériel nécessaire :

Il vous faut un micro switch (voir photo)
Des vis un peu plus longue pour remplacer celles d'origines qui maintiennent l'extruder.
La patte du milieu du switch est à connecter sur le ground (au milieu) de Z- de la MKS
La patte de contact ( ca depend des switchs) est à connecter sur D18 de Z- de la MKS

A configurer dans configuration.h


#define FILAMENT_RUNOUT_SENSOR

  #define ENDSTOPPULLUP_FIL_RUNOUT // Uncomment to use internal pullup for filament runout pins if the sensor is defined.
  #define FILAMENT_RUNOUT_SCRIPT "M600"

I believe this discobolus is a modern retake because the head position is the same as the wrongly restored (thus unique) British Museum replica (see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1894078 and my no-support remix http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2026127), yet obviously different and noticeably more muscular. Authenticity aside, this version arguably has a more impressive physique and probably looks better on your table.

Support just isn't my thing (hate to remove it and hate it more when it leaves a scar on a beautiful model), so I cut the model up into four pieces that can be printed with almost no support and then glued together. See instruction below. My result (150% scale) came out pretty nice. Enjoy!

title: H0 scale model railroad modular bridge

description.text:
H0 modular bridge.
Please take note that the "whole file" is not intended for printing and it serves its purpose showing how the bridge should be assemblied.
It's composed of a "start section", which should be the extremities of the bridge itself, and a central part. Both the start and central sections have a base and two sides
Please be aware of the fact that you should print a number of upper parts in relation to the desired length of the bridge. That is to say, you always need to print a number of upper parts equaling the sum of starts and central part, minus two. (e.g. in the whole file, you have two start and two central section, so it's a total of 4. As you can see, you have only two upper part, which i chose to be both two start upper part, because they are intended to be the terminal section of the bridge cover)

The modules measure 45 mm in lenght each. You can combine them as they are, or you can bring the files to an editor like tinkercad and elongate the central parts to suit your needs.

Note that there are some grooves in the upper part of the bases, they are intended to connect the modules via joint (see joint file) or via simple glue filling.

It's advisable to verify if the plastic used assures the structural resistance needed to support transiting trains. if it bends, you can put a small balsa wood sustain under the base part.
